label: Leadville
description: Harrison Avenue, looking south, c. 1920, Leadville. A view looking south from the 600 block of Harrison Avenue in Leadville, Colorado, showing two and three story brick and wood frame clapboard buildings with pedestrians walking on concrete pavement. Buildings that can be seen include the old Lake County Courthouse with Lady Justice and her scales and the American National Bank with its corner tower dome.
rights: This photo is property of Lake County Civic Center Association.

label: Leadville
description: Laying water line: Men in suits supervise workmen as they install a water pipeline for Leadville (Lake County), Colorado. The pipeline is made of wooden staves and reinforced with metal bands (probably steel). One workman balances a wooden plank on his shoulder while a boy and a man hold buckets. Down the line other workers tighten the metal bands around the pipe.
rights: This photo is property of Lake County Public Library.

label: Documents & Objects
description: Carol Gott's Paleo point from Twin Lakes 1970. In 1970 near Twin Lakes, Mrs. Carol Gott found this classic Plainview Yuma point. The Craftsmanship is so distinctive that the point might serve as a type model. It is an exquisite 4-inch blade chipped from red chert by removal of long, parallel flakes which extend from edge to center. This should date about 8000 B.C.
rights: This photo is property of Lake County Public Library.

description: Margaret "Madge" (Alderson) Shelton, Included was a portion of a newspaper clipping: "Miss Madge Alderson, as Mrs. Sarah Teaberry, had certainly ruined every prospect of future matrimony only for her timely vindication as a very amiable and sweet tempered wife at the close of the second act. Up to that time she had tyrannized over her unfortunate husband in such a realistic manner that the sympathies of the audience were with him, but the reconciliation, when it did come, was comoplete and was a sourse of gratification to those who had been pitying poor Teaberry. Her acting was as good as could have been done."

label: Leadville
description: Leadville, Colo from east end of 8th Street, showing the intersection of E. 8th Street and Alder Street. The steeples of the First Evangelical Lutheran Church, the Church of the Annuncation and the First Methodist Episcopal Church are visible. label: People
description: "Winter Carnival ski joring is a test of the skills and courage of both the rider and the skier plus a trained horse. As the team comes thundering down the ice and snow covered course the rider has to control his horse for the smoothest ride possible while the skier must take the jumps, through the gates, spearing the rings in the most efficient manner. It's no sport for the novice." - J. LeRoy Wingenbach (Wingenbach Collection)
rights: This photo is property of Lake County Public Library.

The rider must be able to guide his horse as close to the jump as is safe and still be ready for the next gate and jump on the opposite side of the course." - J. LeRoy Wingenbach (Wingenbach Collection)

label: People
description: "The various classifications of snowmobiles makes for a number of different types of races in the Leadville Winter Carnival. These varied machine types and sizes race in their own group in the speed races, ten times around a 1/4 mile oval, obstacle races and a cross country race. These events bring snowmobile enthusiasts from all over Colorado and the neighboring states who belong to the racing circuit with their modified machines. The Leadville races in 1972 were part of a Class B Rocky Mountain Snowmobile Association sanctioned race. There are also separate divisions for the amateur racers, for the youngsters and Powderpuff sections for the women." - J. LeRoy Wingenbach (Wingenbach Collection)
rights: This photo is property of Lake County Public Library.

label: Documents & Objects
description: "These are the original badges of membership for the five orders of the Odd Fellows as they existed at the time of the lodges founding in Oro City in 1872. From left to right they are in the following order with the difference being in the color of the rosette at the top - white for those just initiated, pink for the Covenant, royal blue for the Royal Degree, green for Rememberance and Scarlet for the last degree. Green has now been eliminated and combined with the royal blue. This happened around the end of 1880. The rosette at the top, in the proper color was made of wool yarn, the ribbon itself was made of black silk, and the lettering and the tassle of gold. It has a burlap backing on the rosette to which is attached a metal fastener with straight pin to attach to the lothing. The five degree badges are in remarkably good condition despite their 100 years of age." - J. LeRoy Wingenbach (Wingenbach Collection)
rights: This photo is property of Lake County Public Library.

label: People
description: "Just for a bit of diversion at the state muzzle loaders annual shoot at Camp Hale several of the fellows did some firing with their home made mortars. Here two of them have filled the bottom of the mortar with black powder and are now wadding paper into the short bore before putting in a 'charge' of newspapers and wet mud. A beer can complete the charge and it was truely amazing how far the can was shot into the air." - J. LeRoy Wingenbach (Wingenbach Collection)
rights: This photo is property of Lake County Public Library.

label: People
description: "Loading a flintlock is a very precise piece of business. The black powder charge has been measured and poured down the barrel before it is tapped into place as we see being done here. Then the cloth patch and the ball have to be rammed home and then the cap introduced. Mountain Men of old probably would have liked to have had a plastic lunch bucket to hold their equipment such as this shooter had." - J. LeRoy Wingenbach (Wingenbach Collection)
rights: This photo is property of Lake County Public Library.

description: "Six toilet units were built by the Forest Service at the Turquoise Lake Molly Brown Campground at a cost of $15,000 each. They provide hot and cold running water, electrical hand dryers, electric appliance outlets and many other special features. There have been very attractively designed of pre-cast sections and should withstand all attempts at vandalism. Their design blends in well with the rustic mountain surroundings." - J. LeRoy Wingenbach (Wingenbach Collection)
rights: This photo is property of Lake County Public Library.

label: Buildings & Businesses
description: "Serving the total recreation facilities at Turquoise Lake is this modern sewage treatment plant capable of processing 100,000 gallons per day. At the present time this plant will be serving the four toilet units at the Molly Brown Campground plus the ones at the Tabor and Matchless boat ramps. Phased into the system as construction is completed will be the 50 unit Baby Doe campground and the full scale resort area that is in the projection stages." - J. LeRoy Wingenbach (Wingenbach Collection)
rights: This photo is property of Lake County Public Library.
